                    "bio": "Dr. Connie Kais is a graduate of University of the Pacific School of Dentistry San Francisco, one of the best in the country.                     "bio": "Dr. April Schiemenz, MD, is a native Texan who could not wait to return home after training. Her research project investigated the causes and outcomes of late preterm delivery with a focus on finding preventable ways to avoid premature birth.  She was invited to present her data at the ACOG National convention and also won third place in the St. Louis Gynecological Society’s Annual Scientific Meeting.                     "bio": "Boasting a long family history in Fort Worth, Dr. Perkins’ mother claims he always wanted to be a doctor.                 {
                    "address_city": "San Francisco",
                    "bio": "Dr Tran was born in Saigon, Vietnam and her family immigrated to the United States in 1975. Her family settled in Augusta, GA. In 1980, Dr. Tran headed to California to pursue college education.\n\nDr. Tran earned her Bachelor of Science Degree in Cell and Molecular Biology from San Francisco State University in 1985, her Doctorate of Dental Medicine from the Medical College of Georgia in 1990. She joined the Navy Reserve while in dental school. She practiced as a general dentist for 7 years before returning to graduate school. She completed residency training in Periodontics in 2000 at the Naval Post Graduate Dental School in Bethesda, Maryland and became a Diplomate of the American Board of Periodontics in 2000. She completed an additional two year training in Orofacial Pain in 2006 at NPDS, Bethesda and received her board certification in 2007. In 2010, she was selected for acupuncture training with the Helms Medical Institute and received a certificate in Medical Acupuncture. Dr. Tran also received training in Botox injection for TMD and migraine headache from the Allergan® company and the American Academy of Facial Esthetics.\n\nAfter completing Officers’ Indoctrination training at Newport, Rhode Island in August 1990, Dr. Tran reported to Oaknoll Naval Hospital in Oakland, CA as a GPR resident. She went on to serve 12 months in Diego Garcia, a British island in the middle of the Indian Ocean. Then she returned stateside to work at the Marine Corps Recruiting Depot, Parris Island, SC. From 1994-96, she served as the Dental Department Head on the USS Comstock (LSD-45) homeported in San Diego, CA. In 1997 she started residency training in Periodontics and was subsequently assigned to 13 Dental Company, Marine Corps Air Station, Miramar in 2000. In 2004, she returned to Bethesda, MD to complete training in Orofacial Pain. In 2006, she accepted orders to 1st Dental Battalion/Naval Dental Center- Camp Pendleton where she is the department head for Periodontics and Orofacial Pain and mentor for the AEGD and GPR residents.\n\nDr. Tran retired from the US Navy in September 2013 after completing 23 years of active service.                     "address_city": "Greenbrae",
                    "bio": "Dr. Hribar was born in New York, and she moved to the San Francisco Bay Area when she was ten years old. She matriculated to the University of Southern California for medical school, and also conducted a one-year research fellowship in surgical pathology and surgical oncology.                     "description": "An occupational therapist is a person who has graduated from an entry-level occupational therapy program accredited by the Accreditation Council for Occupational Therapy Education (ACOTE) or predecessor organizations, or approved by the World Federation of Occupational Therapists (WFOT), or an equivalent international occupational therapy education program; has successfully completed a period of supervised fieldwork experience required by the occupational therapy program; has passed a nationally recognized entry-level examination for occupational therapists, and fulfills state requirements for licensure, certification, or registration.             "description": "An occupational therapy assistant is a person who has graduated from an occupational therapy assistant program accredited by the Accreditation Council for Occupational Therapy Education (ACOTE) or predecessor organizations, has successfully completed a period of supervised fieldwork experience required by the accredited occupational therapy assistant program, has passed a nationally recognized entry-level examination for occupational therapy assistants, and fulfills state requirements for licensure, certification, or registration.  An occupational therapy assistant provides interventions under the supervision of an occupational therapist which emphasize the therapeutic use of everyday life activities (i.e., occupations) with individuals or groups for the purpose of facilitating participation in roles and situations and in home, school, workplace, community and other settings.  Occupational therapy services are provided for the purpose of promoting health and wellness and are provided to those who have or are at risk for developing an illness, injury, disease, disorder, condition, impairment, disability, activity limitation, or participation restriction.                     "address_city": "Louisville",
                    "bio": "Dr. Wes Allison received his bachelor’s degree in biochemistry at the University of Oklahoma where he was inducted into Phi Kappa Phi Honor Society and graduated with special distinction.
